mon- dc\narchy as a higher and nobler form tj|\n?f government.\nFrance la Place of Fear. 4\nEngland, who has supplied her needs th\nat Germany's cost through the do- w\nstructlon of our naval power, our re\ncolonies and our commerce,' can view m\nthe situation more disinterestedly er\nthan can France, who would neces- Pi\nsarily bear the brunt of possible Ger- co\nman revenge. Fears are felt in al\nFrance that she wfll not receive the in\nauvu uuw uvt* wu *W|\n\"France will whistle for it.\"\nfranco complains also that Ger- 8j\nmany begins the new year in a belli- t]\ncose spirit, citing von Seekt's address q,\nto the army officers, which In its ref- UI\nerence to sharpened swords and i j\nbrightened sheaths was strongly rem- <p\niniscent of Kaiser Wilhelm. His\nglorification, further, of Hollweg is R\nregarded by the b?st Germans as an ni\ninsult. For it was Hollweg whose\ncriminal acts in the summer and au- f(\nturns of 1914 led the German people\nto believe that their country was w\nabout to be made the victim of con- s,\nsplracy and armed attack, and\nthrough false documents spread a na-\ntional conviction that Belgium was a\nAUSTRIA SEES HOPE i\nIN GERMAN UNION f\nw:\nConditions Accentuate Desire S\nw\nfor Amalgamation of Teu- l\\\nru\ntonic People.\nBY A. K- DECKER. G\nm\nBrCtM. to Tbr Star and Chicago Daily Newt.\nCopyright. 1V21.\nVIENNA, January 15.?Austria's elections\nIn the fall of 1920 had little ef- F\nfeet upoo the tendency of political evolution\nin the country. The former social\ndemocratic coalition government fell and\na Christian social government assumed'\nthe leadership. The social democrats\nwhile in power had a decided majority, I i\nbut the Christian socials have only a\nmall plurality.\nThe social democrats In the two years\nthey were In power had time to establish\nelements which If non-destructive\nwere also non-constructive. They allowed\nsomething closely approaching\ncommunism to be organized and developed\nin the minds of the city workmen.\nThey organized a socialist army\nand established a system of food control\nthought by many to be harmful.\nThrough necessity, or for some other\nreason, they printed large quantities of\npaper money without assessing or collecting\ntaxes.\nWould Hnu Stagnation.\nMany Austrlans are asking themselves\nwhat will happen when the government's\ntill is entirely empty and the presses\nare unable to supply the demand for\nthe depreciated currency caused by the\nrising prices. The notes now in circulation\namount to 30.000,004.000 crowns\n(normally $6,000,000,000) and. in addition\nthere is a deficit of the same figuse.\nPrices rise with the inflation. The\nreal sufferers are the middle classes, who\ndepend upon an income from bonds, insurance\nand unorganized labor. An empty\ngovernment till would mean stagnation\nla all government enterprises?food\nrelief and railroad communications.\nThere Is a somewhat less gloomy\nside, however, for the food situation M\nis improved. There is enough food to ?t\nlast until the end of March. Flnan-lfo\nclaQx, a alight betterment in the j oi\nvalue eg (be crown*would make many I be\nAustrian* rich. Thery have half of K\nHOPE LIES\nHONESTLY\nScouting Red Peril\nty of a Sincere\nracy.\narty to this conspiracy, whereas\nuth she was the bleeding victim\nlollweg's failure to keep his agre\nlent.\nIn the official white book he tu\nressed Important telegrams ai\nLherwise poisoned German sentimei\nScoots Bolshevik Peril.\nAs against the wish of France th\nermany proceed honestly to disari\naving nothing under whatever nar\nhich could produce a \"reveni\nrmy,\" It is asserted that German\nnd therefore Europe, must be pr\nared for attack from the Russli\n;d armies and therefore cannot di\nrm. Tnis eventuality is Improbabl\nussia's moujiks constitute 85 p\n;nt of her population. They po\nss land for which they have loi\naited. \"What they now want ai\n?ed is rest.\nMoreover, Lenin would not have d\nded against the communist wish'\ngrant concessions to capitalists hi\ne not perceived the necessity t\nopplng the reign of bloodshed at\nsing all energy for economic recoi\nruction. Everything indicates Rui\na will permit the Polish pear 1\nren and will cease war if the Kra:\nn-Curzon agreement succeeds I\niding the blockade.\nWhat the World Needs.\n!Thfl most imnnrtunt wictioo nf thn<\nho desire humanity's welfare shoul\ns today:\n1. Ti^it countries which have sui\nus food and raw materials shoul\nilckly build bridges to those lai\nlishing for the lack of same, thi\neakenlng the most powerful con\nunist propaganda weapon.\n2. The formation of a union, abov\nispicion, declining all intercours\n1th liars or those desiring the rt\nirn of the old military regime, bu\niving every help to those who hor\nitly desire peaceful democracy an\nle betterment of international rela\n>ns; suppressing aggravating threat:\nich as the occupation of the Rub\nilley, and persevering In the move\nent for general disarmament, Gei\nany leading in disarmament, but nc\noving alone.\n3. That Europe should be regarde\nan economic unity whose suffering\nnot permit a return to selfish na\ninalism, whose wounds are to b\naledcnly on broad economic lines.\nI. That the German people provid\nemselvjs with a government whlc!\nIll not attempt to justify the ol\ngime by continually blaming for\ner enemies, but which will honestl\nnbrace the idea, of a democratic re\niblic, a republic thus earning th\n.nfldence of the world powers an\n>le to insist on a mutual understand\ng as a first condition.\nHopes for World League.\nOnly the. fulfillment of these de\ndorato will pIpop tho nlr fnr ttiA MP*\nement of the difficult reparation\naestion, which cannot take plac\nitil the league of nations becomes\nring- organism, Instead of a torsi\nhe league should be the noble meat\ninternational discussion, includin\nussia, which at worst is not bloodie\nit baser than under the czar, incluc\nig also America, which, overcomin\nselings of disappointment and abai\nming a policy of fruitless negatioi\nould, despite her position of worl\nlpremacy, co-operate toward ti\narvest of spring blossoms and son\nier fruit.\n(Copyright. 1921.)\nelr funds in foreign money, as the\nlow that there is no real none\nLck of their own paper currenc;\ntie Austrians have considered tt\ntuatlon hopeless and have felt thi\nily outside aid would be effectiv\n3T this reason they have made ai\nsals to the entente and have talke\na union \\9ith Germany.\nL'aloa WiA Germany Favored,\nlust now the propaganda for unitln\nith Germany is more accentuate\nan ever before. In Austria the s(\nal democrats and pan-Germans bot\nould like a union, the former t\nrengthen the power of the city s<\nalists against the Christian socii\niraiists, and the latter to unite a\nople of the German race. Otb<\nustrians consider thai a union wli\nermany would be a climax to the\nisfortune.\nailed in Effort to Form\nNew French Cabin<\n,\\*Sfc '^1\n\\i H\n3 v A\ni\nM. RAOUL PERBT.\nIcoordlac to reports Croat Pari\nPrrftt, president of the Fren<\nsmbrr of deputies, was unable i\nrat a new cabinet to ouececa tbi\nGeorges U/guts, nslgmei, aft\ninp- nqtcfUi todo ao tp PttaUe\nlllerand.\nMEAL A DAY SAVES\nMANY UTILE ONES\nL\nBenefit of the American Relief\nWork In Austria\nApparent.\naim Aiiipai nnnr TOO ArtO\nqf aiu uivtn rnurcaauna\ne\nCereals and Fats Will Be Exhaustp\nud ed Next Month?Chancellor Says\n1L Country Faces Bankruptcy.\nBY A. R. DECKER.\na By Cable to The Star and Chicago Dally News,\nrn. Copyright, 192T.\n,,e VIENNA, Austria, January 15.?This\n'e noon I visited the old artillery barracks,\nY. where the American relief admlnistrae\ntion is feeding several thousand children\nin of Vienna, giving each child one nours\nlshlng meal daily at a cost of 7 cents,\nle. Three hundred thousand Austrian\ner children are being fed and of these\ns- 160,000 are in Vienna\nig If Relief Were Withdrawn,\nid I asked Dr. Plrquet, an Austrian child\nexpert, working with the administration:\ne- \"What would happen if the relief work\nP9 were withdrawn?\"\n\"The children would quickly revert to\nia their former condition of undernourtshof\nment.\" he replied. \"Not only would\n1(j their American food be gone, but they\nwould have to be fed from the small\nAustrian stock, thus doubling the dis- j\ng_ aster. Indeed, food would not be ob-1\ntalnable and they would have to. go hungry.\"\ns- Dr. Plrquet further told the writer\nIn that the children had shown a wonderful\nImprovement since the feeding began,\nthe percentage of the very badly nourished\nclass having been greatly reduced.\nThe school attendance has been lnle\ncreased by 25 per cent.\nId Nearly All Undernourished.\nOf the children in Vienna 97 per cent\nr. were found to be undernourished, but\nit was found impossible to feed all\nH 1 J~ J tUa\nwim cne iuuus pruviuru. iiniLr 111\ni- children were classified Into three\ngroups. Then It had to be decided\nwhether to feed few three meals\nI- daily or provide one meal a day to all\nthe most needy. It was decided to give\n300.000 one meal. Hence, while the\n0 work Is wide In scope It does not cover\nie the need. Austria has 1,182,000 children\nup to fifteen years of age. Of\nthese 930.000, upon scientific medical\nexamination, were found to be urideri\nnourished and only one-third fed. All\nd the very badly nourished are being\nfed and three-quarters of the badly\nl\" nourished class.\na. In two of Vienna's poorer districts. 7\nper cent of the children receive only\nAmerican food. In other districts the\nchildren are supposed to receive something\nat home, for the American meal\n,t is intended to be supplementary.\nAM for Professor*,\nd The Rochester community fund has\nbeen devoted to organising a co-oper:s\naitive restaurant for Vienna professors.\nIn a transformed billiard room\ne the professors come as to a dub and\nfor a small payment receive a simple\nbut good meal. The club is popular\ne and was certainly needed, for a proI,\nfeasor earns only about $10 a month\nin money. No one is prosperous exa\ncept the \"schlehers\" or profiteers, be\ncause the cost of living hgi increased\ny 100 times and wages and salaries but\nfive times.\nPew persons actually die of hunger,\ne but. being underfed, they fall easy vie\na tints to disease. Inlant mortality and\ntuberculosis have increased 30 per\ncent.\nAustria Is \"Broke.\"\nAustria is \"broke.\" and, the writer\nunderstands, has been forced to pledge\nGobelin tapestries for food. Feb _\nruary will see the end of the stocks\nof cereals and fats, after Which any18\nthing can be expected, for the unem?\nployed cannot live on the government\na aid of 3 cents a day.\nA few days ago. almost in the form\nof a New Year call. Chancellor Mayr\nis visited the foreign representatives in\ng Vienna and practically declared that\nAustria was facing bankruptcy. The\n!r withdrawal or restriction of American\ni- aid, he said, would add starvation to\ng Austria's black outlook.\n1 SIMPLER PASSPORT RULES\n2 DEMANDED IN EUROPE\ni- _______\nTravelers Claim Big financial\nLosses by Del -ys at\n!y Frontiers,\nj: BERLIN, January 15.?There is a\nLt spontaneous demand from commercial\ne. organisations of Europe and the\nAmerican -continent for simpler passport\nregulations, says Fred W. King,\nacting president of the American\ng Chamber of Commerce of this city,\nd The matter already has been brought\nto the attention of a number of gov*\nernments and protests have been\nmade to Washington against the\nal American system of issuing short^\ntime passports, it is stated,\n'h Representatives of chambers of\nir commerce of many nations are to\nhold a conference for the purpose of\ndeveloping a passport plan that will\nbe at once satisfactory to the governments\nand meet the needs of com\nmercial and other travelers.\n;t Those advocating: changes want\npassports to be issued for. perhaps,\na number of years, instead of for a\nfew months. aDd to eliminate the custom\nof viseing, ipspection and long\nexaminations at every frontier. It j\nis claimed that the delays resulting\nfrom present regulations have been\ncarried to a most aggravating extent\nby some of the smaller nations\nOf central Europe.\n\"Business men have told me of losing\nhundreds of thousands of dollars\nby being unable to keep appointments\nand close contracts because of delays\nin receiving credentials to cross the\nfrontiers,\" said Mr. King. \"The present\nsystem is absolutely hopeless\nfrom a business viewpoint. What is\nneeded is a simple method which will\ndo away with all the red tape and\npermit people to move about as\nquickly as affairs require. This is\nentirely possible.\"\nHIT BY GERMAN RIVALRY.\nSweden's Employers Lose Through\nCompetition in Markets.\nSTOCKHOLM. January 12.?Swedish\nemployers are feeling the brunt of\nGerman competition. Its pressure has\nbecome so great that proprietors of\na large number of Swedish industrial\nand other enterprises have been compelled\nto enter into negotiations with\ntheir employes, placing before them\nthe alternatives of a reduction of\nwages or the number of workmen.\nThe employers say they will be un?.\nable to keep their works in operation\nat the present rate of financial loss,\nto The mechanical engineering Indusst\ntry Is particularly hard bit by _<Sbm _r\npetition from Germany, where wages\nst are a mere fraction of the -Swedish\nrates of compensation.\nViviani Ma\nfor Amerk\nBY RE\n(By Cal\nPARIS, Jan-\nuary 15.?I thank\nthe Washington\nStar for the opportunlty\nof ad- ^f#\ndressing directly\nthe American\npublic. The ^^BL\npresent epoch is\nFin forfiia i-? ?1~\nund erstandings fcEpJPfflpi\nthat It Is neces?ary\nthat we\nhave frequent ft\ne x c h a nges of .fj\nideas. Between\nFrance and H^K|||||[|\nAmerica ,these ^HBp?|||pr\nx c h a nges\nmind\nc h a nges\nheart, for they H^HHEjC\nproceed from a\ncommon cononly\nbecause\ntheir tragedies. KEY\ntwice shared. Former\nare these two\ngreat republics\nnear to each other, but also be\ncause they emerge from the wa\nthe two least selfish nations.\nYet misunderstandings separat\nthem. Reproaches do not hell\nthey serve only to embitter; com\npliments do not help, they onl\nbreed insincerity. We must te\neach other the truth. That is th\nbest course for honest people. T\nknow what one wants, to te\nwhere one is going, to tell otheri\nand to keep one's word is the onl\ndiplomacy possible for great pec\npies, and their ambassadors ar\ntheir citizens.\n\nImmediately after the war a\nevil opinion surrounded Franc\nlike a thick veil. Poor France\nShe truly IB uniucnyi ociurc in\nwar she was the object of tyimili\natlng pity for her ancient distress\nafter the war she aroused a.n env\nthat seeks to tarnish her glor:\nShe is accused of imperialism, o\nendangering world peace and o\nthrowing- Europe into economi\nand financial disorder tbroug\nstubbornness. So much for th\ngeneral reproaches.\nThe France which lay conquere\nfor forty-four years did not wan\nwar. She tried to avoid it. Sh\nsigned five transactions in te\nyears toward world peace. Noi\nshe has become imperialistic\nWhy? Because she maintains a\narmy? She has just reduced th\nperiod of military service, but re\nI tains troops in the field. Why doe\nshe? What is her role in th\nj world? France is a peaceft\ndemocracy. She had ojily one de\nsire, namely, to see Alsace retur\nhome. She possesses in norther\n\"Africa and in Senegal a territor\nwhere Justice has inspired the na\ntives with affection. She must re\ni build her own economic fortune\nand repair countless ruins, bend\nIng double with toil to clear her\nself of innumerable obligations.\n\nHow can she be accused of blac!\ndesigns? True, she retains a\narmy of 700,000, but others hav\nkept their fleets. It must be re\nmembered that France is alongsid\nGermany, a uermany wnicn sun naxe\nand which has a weak grovernmen\nSEES FRA1N\nGERMANS\nEditor of Echo de\nAlternative Is\nto Insigni\nBY PEHTIKAX.\nBy Cable to The Star.\nPARIS. January 15.?Although t\ndefeat of the Leygues ministry in t\nchamber of deputies last Wednesd\nwas fully predicted in these d\npatches several weeks ago, nobo\nquite has realized .the difficult po\ntion in which this would lea\nFrance. The achievement of Leygt\nas premier is that of having been\npower four months without e\\\nhaving expressed any definite vie\non any definite subject, and he drc\nped from the position of head of t\nFrench government as an overri\napple falls from a tree.\nThe problem now confronting t\npresident of the .republic, who mi\nfind a new premier capable\nchoosing a ministry acceptable to t\npeople, really Is less that than t\nre-establishment of that gover\nmental authority which almost h\ndisappeared through lack of exerci\nDownfall of Leygiin.\nThe personal insignificance of t\noutgoing premier must not be e\ncepted, however, as sufficient exp]\nnation of his fate. The real can\nlies deeper in post-war French po\ntics. It is the fact that the task\nenforcing French rights Under t\npeace treaty is so great and diffici\nthat not only has every man who h\ntried his hand at it failed, but th\nail good men suggested as possii\nendeavorers fear the Job.\nThat section of the treaty whi\nconcerns reparations is now foremc\nin importance, as the nation's ec\nnomic reconstruction depends up\nit. Therefore, it inevitably is t\ndominant factor in the present i\nlationships of France with her alii\nand associates. By one leader aft\nanother the French people have be\nled to expect from Germany a coi\npensation extending far beyond pra\ntlcal possibilities.\nFeared French Outburst.\nWhen the treaty \\ya? .ifi the makh\nat Versailles, Clemenceau,\" Tardt\nand.Loucheur all were afraid to sta\nany fixed sum to be paid by the Ge\nmans, dreading popular French ou\ncry, and the result was the postpon\nkes a Plea\n;a's Friendship\n:XE VIVIAXL\nlie to The Star.)\nSo nobody can be\nsure but\nLudendorf or the\ncommunists will\nattempt to over\nernment.\n|l I Does America\nrealize what we\nhave lost and\n|p what we have\nA rtf rnurAe Re\na cause American\ngene roslty toward\nus has\nbeen limitless.\nBut perhaps\nAmerica believes\nthat we have\nno reason to\nfear the future,\nforgetting that\nwe have mounted\nguard beside\na volcano.\nE VIVIAN! The u'r\nremlcr of France r0r 18 be,'ef\n______________ that the peace\ntreaty brought\ni- peace, whereas it only ended hosr\ntillties and stopped a massacre.\nAt present we are between war\ne and peace, and the latter will exist\nonly when nationalist passions and\ni- revengeful desires and hates are\ny calmed and when economic sell\ncurity returns. What is needed\ne to bring this about? It Is neceso\nsary that Germany keep her enU\ngagements, for Germany brought\n3, on this economic situation by\ny war. Not only in the interest of\nright must she make reparation,\ne but in the interest of every one In\nthe world. If Europe, which is already\nthe tomb of millions, conn\ntinues living thus, with work,\ne energy and production paralyzed,\nEurope will not suffer alone. It\ne is no longer possible for a nation\nto maintain isolation. Economic\ni; interest, if not ideals, demand that\ny all nations, linked by commercial\nr. necessity, present a common front.\nif\n,f A united Europe in Its present\nc distress will buy nothing, sell\nh nothing. What can the world do\ne against mat; ui course, tne peace\ntreaty failed to foresee such\nd things, but that Is no reason to\nit spend a lifetime groaning about it.\ne The treaty is written. We French,\nn who more than any soaked it in\nk our innocent blood, consider it our\ncharter. The fury of battles did\nn not destroy our. wealth. It was a\ne systematic rival who sought to\ni- bredk our power of recovery. War\ns is ignominious, but victory would\nbe immoral If the victors, who are\nil likewise victims, went without\nreparation,\nn\nn France has but one interest;\ny namely, to rebuild herself alongside\nher countless graves, and\ni- everything else is unselfish, is diss\ninterested, like America. But, like\nAmerica, we are interested in the\nfinal triumph of right.\nThey say we don't agree on the\nmeans. It is enough that we agree\nk on the end, and this we do. But\nn belief or faith in universal right\ne cannot be resorted to except on the\n'basis of respect for international\ne engagements. Otherwise that\ns right would be a delusion,\nt. (Copyright, 1921.)\nICE FACING\nALL ALONE\nParis Fears the Onlj\nReducing Claims\nc/\nificant Point.\nment of fixation until May 1. 1921. ii\nMay and June of last year Milieram\nendeavored to settle the matter witl\nhe England and the other allies. H\nhe stressed the fact that the treaty doe\nnot provide coercive action by the al\ny lies and that without such actioi\nis- Germany cannot be expected to pay\ndy urging willingness to make the treat;\nin other respects less drastic if th'\nallies would Join him in the applica\nvfc; tion of coercive measures, whethe\nies they had been written in or not. Hi\nnearly succeeded in reaching his goal\n1 but jeopardized his whole undertak\n'er ing by his failures at the Spa con\nW3 ference with regard to subordinati\nmatters. The fact, too,-generally es\ncapes attention abroad tha^, despit\nhe his success with regard to Poland\npe Millerand went to the Elysee Palac<\nas President of France a half-defeat\ned man. if success is the achievemen\nhe of all that one starts out to do. Mori\nist ?r less assisted by Leygues. his pol\nof icy has been to force a determlnatioi\nhe of some fixed sum, screened by an un\nhe ceasing public defense of a literal in.\nn. terpretation of the Versailles treaty!\"\nas Crumbling of Ministry.\nse- Such was the French policy jus\nclosed with the overthrow of Leygues\nhe Since inability to solve the reparation\nIC. problem unavoidably implies upon th\nia_ part of a French government Inabilit;\ni8e to control the course of home and for\njj_ eign policies, the gradual ruin of th\nof ministry's prestige and authority wil\nhe he easily understood. A fact hitherti\njtt secreted Is that during the last few o\nas his days In office Leygues, apparentl;\n,at without consultation with anybody, tool\nlie the risky initiative of communicating ti\nthe British government his resolve t(\nch abandon all hope of rating a total of thi\n>st joint German debt, and declared that hi\n10- should rest content with fixing five an\non nual payments of 300,000,000 marks gol<\nhe each, which he should call upon Ger\ne- many to pay pending the settlement ol\nes the whole reparations problem. Ol\ner course, he selected such a solution been\ncause it allowed him to represent tc\nn- parliament that he really had not tol.c\nerated a curtailment of the ultimate\nFrench claims and that the plan merelj\npostponed that day when an accurate\nand satisfactory statement of Germany't\ncapacity to-pay would become possiblete\nDanger In Initiative.' r\nThis initiative on the part of Premier\nit- Leyguea was very dangerous, as it is\ne- obvious that the longer France waits\nRUSSIAN OUTRAGES\n1 SI LABOR LEADER\nMetal Workers' Secretary at\nParis Acts in Behalf of\nSocial Democrats.\nWORLD REBUKE FAVORED\nLeader in General Confederation\nPresents Series of Documents\nto Show Terrorism.\nmm M M *M*j u avu i r aiuwnEin*\nBy Cable to Tlie Stnr and Clilrago Dally Mews.\nCopyright, 1921.\nPARIS, January 13.?A. Merrhelm,\nsecretary of the Metal Workers'\nUnion, and one of the leaders of the\nGeneral Labor Confederation, calls\non the International Trades Union to\nprotest against the terrorism by\nwhich the Russian communists are\ntrying to repress the social democratic\nparty In Russia.\nAfter presenting a series of documents,\nmostly from socialist sources,\nhe goes on to say:\n\"Such are the facts. Equally with\nthose in Hungary, regarding which\nI the international trades unions have\nalready been protesting, there should\narise the vehement and indignant\nreprobation of all trades union members\nand socialists who still have a\nsense of dignity and independence.\"\n\"Various Instances Cited.\nInstances are cited by M. Merrheim\nfrom the documentary evidence.\nThe arrests attendant on the alleged\nsocial democratic conspiracy\nlast September necessitated 4,000 new\nplaces In the Moscow concentration\ncamps, to procure which the bolsheviki\nsent 4,000 of the older prisoners\nto Ekaterinburg and Archangel.\nAmong the prisoners sent to Ekaterinberg\nwere several leaders of the\ncenter party and the co-operative\nunion.\nThe trip took ten days. On the way\nthe prisoners received no hot food\nand no hot water. Moreover, the\nEkaterinburg authorities had not\nbeen warned of their coming and\nthere was no place for them in the\nmi?.. 1\nvTctv.iuwucu jtx.ua. xucjr ncic ivcpi\ntwo days in the station and a month\nin a half-built house, and then were\nfinally thrown into jail with common\ncriminals.\nIn October and November there\nwere mass arrests of social democrats.\nIn Mogile all the leaders of\nthe party except two were arrested.\nTwelve, leaders were arrested at\nVitebsk and twenty at Samara. At\nSmolensk the president of the committee\nand several members were\narrested. There were arrests and\nseizures of property at Stavropol,\nKursk. Nijninovogorod, Sormovo and\nVologda. In Briansk an influential\nmetal worker. Samsonov, was thrown\ninto jail. There are now twenty-six\nsocial democrat leaders in the Moscow\nprison.\nArrested at Party Congress.\nMany of the leaders of the Ukrainian\nsocial democrats were arrested\nAugust 19 during the party\" congress\nat Kharkov. Seventeen of these have\nbeen exiled to Georgia and others\nhave been condemned to forced labor\nin the concentration camps \"until the\nend of the civil war.\" Among the\nlatter is Kutchline Gransky, the socialist\nwriter, who volunteered in the\nred army at the beginning of the\ncampaign against Poland.\nMembers of the central committee\nof the social revolutionary party\nafter a long sojourn in the Karoslav\njail have been removed much enfeebled\nto the Butyrki prison, in\nMoscow.\nThis Karoslav jail is famous\nthroughout Russia. On August 11, as\na protest against ill-treatment, the\nprisoners declared a hunger strike.\nThe authorities immediately retaliated\nby removing the ringleaders to\na dungeon.\nAll prisoners thenceforth were forbidden\nto receive visitors, receive or\nsend letters, read newspapers or receive\nfood packages, without which\nthev must slowly starve.\nThe daily fare in this wrison. consists.\nin the morning, of 300 grams\n(about ten and one-half ounces) of\nblack bread, \"like putty.\" and a cup\nof hot water; at noon, a thin soup\nwith a few pieces of potato, beet and\ncabbage and a few herring heads, and\nat night two spoonfuls of mashed\npotatoes.\nI Threat to Striken.\nM. Merrheim then quotes this re'\nsume of a communique in the official\nnewspaper Pravda:\n\"The workmen in the Bkftterinoslav\nsteel mills having gone on a\nstrike and committed numerous acts\nT of sabotage, the soviet government\nhas effected a military occupation of\nthe mills and given the workmen\nforty-eight hours in which to resume\nwork. At the expiration of this time\nthe striking workmen and their families\nwill be arrested and interned\nin concentration camps in northern\nRussia.\"\n\"In the face of these acts, com?\nmitted by the Russian communists,\nj are we going to make ourselves ack\ncomplices by our silence?\" asks M.\ne Merrhein. To do so, he thinks, would\ns be to surrender the principle of soli.\ndarity in unionized labor.\n\"LIFER\" GETS FREEDOM.\nB\nServes 15 Years When Heal Mure\nderer Confesses.\nGENEVA. January 15.?After serv\"\ning more than fifteen years of a life\n_ sentence for a murder of which he has\ne always claimed to be innocent, a\nyoung man named Hirschbrunner is\nI to be released, the real culprit having\nt confessed.\ne On the day following a popular\nmasked ball at Soleure in May, 1906.\n1 the body of'a young Swiss girl was\nfound in the waiting room of the rail\"\nroad station where she had been\nstrangled to death. She had been seen\nthe previous evening in the company\nit of a young man dressed as a peasant\nwoman. The deucription of her coms\npanion tallied with a costume worn by\ne Hirschbrunner and he was tried and\nY sentenced to life imprisonment, en_\ntirely on circumstantial evidence.\n1\nf for the audit of her'accounts the less\nshe will be in a position to rally her\nallies to her support if she finds it neces*\nsary to attempt enforcement of her\nI claims.\nThe detachment of America from anyikimor\n1 lira Alton tka aaiMklnnhA yvf\nwuiiq \"no o?vi? mo ooiwoiaiioo vi aoiivc\nparticipation in th? enforcement of the\nJ Versailles treaty indicates that before\nlong France will have to choose between\nreducing her claims against Germany\nto insignificance or embarking upon the\nI hazardous enterprise of separate military\nj action, such as would estrange her from i\nj her former friends. For such reasons it\nis devoutly and almoBt tremulously\nhoped by all far-seeing Frenchmen that i\nin the choice of a successor to Leygues\nMillerand will be more successful than\nhe was in the selection of Leyguee him'\nself and that the allies, realizing the\nvast amount of that which is at stake,\nwill not (rahecessarily make the path of\nt the French government more difficult.\nI (Copyright, 1921.)\n\nWANTS U. S\nIN CURTA1\nBritish Lahor Leadi\nfor America to\nof the\nBY GEORGE N. BARNES,\nBritish Labor Leader.\nBy Cable to The Star.\nLONDON. Jan?Amer\niea has a great\nopportunity today,\nfor the time V\nis propitious for B flPBBB\ncourageous lead B[ JUL .JjaKjjBj\nin lessened 'llPwljf\narmament\no^cuuiiig. x 111* ^JSHHB\nBritish naval ^jjpP^SIP\nprogram is in jBB|\nabeyance; Japan\nhas asked a\nhalt; D'Annunzio's legionaries have\nbeen blown out of Fiume by a blast\nof public Impatience; th French\nmilitarists have been defeated in the\nchamber of deputies and, above all,\npeoples everywhere afe sick of war.\nShould America point the way, the\nleague of nations would assuredly\nfollow her lead in this direction, for\nthe assembly, with Anglo-Japanese\nconcurrence, has declared in favor\nof the limitation of armaments.\nEndanger Peace of the World.\nViscount Grey is one of the safest\nand sanest men and he, perhaps more\nthan any other man in Great Britain,\naccurately senses the present needs.\nWorthy, indeed, of the man was his\nspeech in Glasgow the other day.\nwhen he said that' armaments still\nendangered the peace of the world,\nand he urged that their growth be\ncarefully watched, and, if possible,\narrested, so that no country might\nagain force the killing pace. He\ncommented upon the ghastly precedent\nof a victorious Germany forcing\nthe Franco-Russian alliance by\nforming the triple combination of\nGermany, Austria and Italy, and he\nwarned against the possibilities of\nallied exclusiveness, now that we are\nin the position Germany held fifty\nyears ago.\nWill these wise words be heeded?\nTo me it seems that the time has\ncome, not only to check the growth\nbut concurrently lessen all firearms;\nyet the only relief is in the reduction\nof expenditures, and here is America's\nopportunity for leadership.\nLeague of A at Ions Stronger.\nThe league of nations has been\nj strengthened by the first plenary\nmeeting. The Argentine delegates'\nwithdrawal when their amendments\nwere not accepted concerned nobody\nseriously. Therefore, the Argentine\npresident is probably sorry now that\nhe forced his country briefly into undesired\nprominence. The league may\nmodify the covenant to get the cooperation\nof all nations, but it wont\nbe bullied. It has come to stay and\nhas the backing of peoples, who will\nJAPANESE STATUS\nTO FOREINMDA\nPress Discusses Reports\nThat Cruisers May Co-Operate\nWith U. S. in Pacific.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nOTTAWA, January 15.?The California-Japanese\nquestion is again to the\nfore, now that .there have been intimation\nfrom New York that certain\nCanadian cruisers are to go to th%\nPacific coast, possibly to confederate\nwith United States ones in anticipation\nof some possible future Japanese\nmenace.\nThere is nothing to this; at least\nnothing but what both Americans and\nCanadians now universallv acknowl-\nedge?that is, that both countries I\nhave the same views respecting what 1\nis generally known as the \"yellow\nperil.\"\nThe Globe, Toronto, one of Canada's\n\nLord Reading, Who May\nBecome Viceroy of India\nvX'J\nMr\n^r-' fl p* I\nBflHHHHHHBBSE\nI'kr Karl of Heading. lord chief juatlcr\nof Kngland, woo fame at Ihr bar\naa Rufua Daniel Iaaaca. H? ia widely 1\nknown in thin country, bavin* been\nencaged In diplomatic and financial i\nmiaalonx duriuur the war. t\nv I\nBritain, would, according to recen\ncourt decisions, be attachable for inpayment\nof former debts, and even i\nthis were legislatively overcome. n<\ngovernment could rely, without guui\nantees, upon the bond of a goveri\nI ment which prides itself on perjur;\nThere must be something in the nn\nture of clearing houses, either fre\nports in Russia or other receiving sta\ntions, until such time as there is\nresponsible Russian government, o\nthe present government shows\nchange of heart and intent.\nImprovement In Irelandj\nIreland is still in a ferment, although\nthere are signs of improve\nment. The home rule bill has becorr.t\na law and therein lies the promise o\nfurther improvement. In a few week\nnorthern Irishmen -will be proceedinto\nset up a new parliament and ther>\nmay be a psychological infection Ithe\nsouth aud West, where peon\nwhile still holding a vision of futur\nfreedom, may yet decide to accept th<\nact. A fateful stage for Ireland an.Great\nBritain lias been reached. It i.\nIreland's turn to speak. Will she\nspeak for a measure of peace and reconciliation?\nWill she try to build on\nthe basis of the new act? 1 hope she\nmay.\n(Copyright, 1921.)\nmost reliable publications, shows tha;\neven if authorities did at any stage\nconsider the possibility of similai\nviews with respect to oriental immigration.\nthat is no reason for the assumption\nthat because Canadian\ncruisers are going to the Pacific Coast\nwaters they are to confederate In any\nway with American vessels.\nThe Globe shows that the vessels\nare en route to patrol the Paclic coast\non ordinary duty.\n'The London Daily News.\" says the\nGlobe editor, \"prints a fantastic story\nfrom its American correspondent:\n\"Mr. P. W. Wilson alleges an informal\ncompact between the Canadian\ngovernment and the republican\nparty of the United States, by which\nthe new Canadian squadron, the gift\nof the British admiralty, is to proceed\nto the Pacific coast to co-operate with\nthe American fleet under a unified\ncommand, using the United States\nnaval bases on the Pacific.\nYarn Called Imagination.\n\"Mr. Wilson's yarn is Imaginative,\nbut it is mischievous also, because it\nimplied that Canada, immediately\nupon receiving the admiralty gift, had\nproceeded to make use of it to af\nI front Japan. Great Britain's ally.\nwithout Great Britain's knowledge or\nconsent. The Canadian ships?two\ndestroyers and two submarines?are\non their way to the Pacific coast, but\nnot because of any understanding\nwith the 1'nited States or Japan.\nThere are plenty of British warships\non the Atlantic, and the Canadian\ngovernment has chosen to use its own\nto patrol the Pacific coast, where\nthere is an excellent Canadian naval\nbase?at Ksquimalt. Canada is attending\nstrictly to her own business.\n\"The fact that Canada and all the\nBritish dominions fronting on the\nPacific are as much opposed to\nAsiatic immigration as the United\nStates will no doubt be a factor in\nBhaping the policy of the British government\nand the terms of any new\nAnglo-Japanese agreement.\nNothing Inimical to 1'. S.\n\"The T'nited States may be assured\nthat, whatever may be the outcome\nof the present negotiations for the\nrenewal of the Anglo-Japanese\ntreaty, there will be nothing in it\ninimical to the interests of the United\nStates. The Japanese ambassador\nin London, Baron Hayashi, points out\nthat Great Britain is expressly absolved\nin the present treaty from\njoining Japan in a war against the\nUnited States, and that the AngloJapanese\nalliance can never stand in\nthe way of friendly relations between\nthe United States and Great Britain.\nBut the presence of a Canadian squad\n<ion in me eacinc win na\\e no eon neetlon\nwhatever with Anglo-Japanese\nor Anglo-American negotiations.\nIt is merely the employment of Canadian\nships in a purely Canadian.\ntask.\"\nFORTUNE FOR FILIPINOS.\nMethodist Episcopal Church to\nSpend Million in Islands.\nMANILA, p. I.. January 15.?a million\nand a quarter dollars will he\nspent in the Philippine Islands by the\nMethodist Episcopal Church in the\nnext five years, according to Dr.\nJoseph F. Cottlngham. conference\nevangelist of the local Methodist mission.\nwho has just reiu-ned to the\nislands after an absence of two years.\nThe mission plans to erect 500 buildings\nand to participate In the construction\nof two educational institutions.\n\nA\nTO LEAD\n[LING ARMS\n:r Sees Opportunity\nPromote Peace\nWorld.\nAnally determine the attitude of politicians\nand presidents.\nAll in the Name Boat.\nThe new Cunard line stock Issue of\nfour million sterling- (normally about\n$20,000,000) to complete Us shipbuilding\nprogram shows notable enterprise\nanH rnnflHonTt ic r*Vio/?rir?e? Hti\ning to the somber cloud of depression\nhanging over the industrial world.\nBut a return to prosperity depends\nupon the re-establishment of credit\nof countries desolated by the war so\nthey may again buy from countries\nlike America, where productive capacity\nhas been only slightly impaired.\nWe are all in the same boat and must\npull together if wo desire to surmount\ncommercial depression, unemployment\nand class conflict.\nIt is also satisfactory to note that\nthe financial economic organisation\ngrowing out of th